KB00004613,395.6457,Hutt Minoh Friendship House,"A Japanese cultural centre in Normandale, Lower Hutt, created from the sister city relationship between Lower Hutt and Minoh, Osaka, Japan. It is administered by the Hutt Minoh House Friendship Trust. Offers classes in Japanese culture and holds public events each year. The Hutt Minoh Friendship Club is for people interested in learning more about Japanese culture.",https://www.cab.org.nz/community-directory/KB00004613,False,True,"['moving to new zealand', 'cultural activities']",ServiceProvider,,['Wellington'],"['Lower Hutt', 'Upper Hutt']","A Japanese cultural centre in Normandale, Lower Hutt, created from the sister city relationship between Lower Hutt and Minoh, Osaka, Japan. It is administered by the Hutt Minoh House Friendship Trust. Offers classes in Japanese culture and holds public events each year. The Hutt Minoh Friendship Club is for people interested in learning more about Japanese culture. The House in Normandale is available for small conferences and private functions - bookings through Hutt City Council 570 6666.  Facebook page  - https://www.facebook.com/huttminoh/      ","

A Japanese cultural centre in Normandale, Lower Hutt, created from the sister city relationship between Lower Hutt and Minoh, Osaka, Japan.
It is administered by the Hutt Minoh House Friendship Trust. Offers classes in Japanese culture and holds public events each year.
The Hutt Minoh Friendship Club is for people interested in learning more about Japanese culture.
The House in Normandale is available for small conferences and private functions - bookings through Hutt City Council 570 6666.

KB00038907,395.57346,Taita Community Library ,"Taita Community Library is one of 8 libraries that make up Hutt City Libraries.  It holds print and digital books, newspapers, magazines, DVDs, and CDs. Online resources can be accessed free for borrowers with a library card, including Generosity NZ (for funding applications), Ancestry.com and Findmypast (for family history research), Road to IELTS (for English language practice), Beamafilm (for streaming movies and documentaries), and Story Box Library (for children).",https://www.cab.org.nz/community-directory/KB00038907,False,True,"['adult education', 'volunteering & community organisations', 'cultural activities']",ServiceProvider,,['Wellington'],['Lower Hutt'],"Taita Community Library is one of 8 libraries that make up Hutt City Libraries.  It holds print and digital books, newspapers, magazines, DVDs, and CDs. Online resources can be accessed free for borrowers with a library card, including Generosity NZ (for funding applications), Ancestry.com and Findmypast (for family history research), Road to IELTS (for English language practice), Beamafilm (for streaming movies and documentaries), and Story Box Library (for children). Hutt City Libraries also run a range of events for all ages throughout the city including storytime and book groups, author and science talks, regular fun events for tamariki and their whānau, school holiday activities, computer classes and JP clinics. For more information go to the website or talk to staff.  ","

KB00038168,244.55858,Seido Karate Lower Hutt,"Seido Karate Lower Hutt Dojo is a family values oriented dojo. The Seido Juku style of Karate was founded on three underlying principles: Love, Respect and Obedience. KB00020430,219.346,Hutt Multicultural Council Inc,"Hutt Multicultural Council promotes ethnic diversity in Lower Hutt. The Council supports migrants, refugees and overseas students through multicultural events, workshops, and networking.  Meets on 1st Thursday each month and new members are always welcome.  Email the secretary for details of meeting place. KB00038187,173.26035,Mary Rodgers Dance Academy,"Mary Rodgers Dance Academy provides dance lessons in Lower Hutt. They offer ballet, American jazz and pilates for children of all ages and abilities. They have two purpose-built studios. Royal Academy of Dance syllabus is taught to ballet students and examinations are offered, but not compulsory. This syllabus focuses on traditional classical ballet technique which provides a strong foundation for all other dance forms. New students can enrol at any time during the year. ",https://www.cab.org.nz/community-directory/KB00038187,False,True,['cultural activities'],ServiceProvider,,['Wellington'],['Lower Hutt'],"Mary Rodgers Dance Academy provides dance lessons in Lower Hutt. They offer ballet, American jazz and pilates for children of all ages and abilities. They have two purpose-built studios. Royal Academy of Dance syllabus is taught to ballet students and examinations are offered, but not compulsory. This syllabus focuses on traditional classical ballet technique which provides a strong foundation for all other dance forms. New students can enrol at any time during the year.  A registration form is on the website.  Prospective students can visit a class before committing to ongoing tuition. Teachers are Royal Academy Registered.  the Academy has a purpose-built Pilates Equipment Studio available for private tuition for dance students.      ","

KB00020484,141.68304,Wainuiomata Historical Museum Society Inc,"The Wainuiomata Historical Society was established in 1977.  In March 1987 the Wellington Education Board gave the use of the ‘old school’, a 1908 heritage building, to the Society.  The Museum was opened on 30 September 1989 by Harry Martin, the first and only Mayor of Wainuiomata.",https://www.cab.org.nz/community-directory/KB00020484,False,True,"['volunteering & community organisations', 'running a society or charity', 'cultural activities', 'new zealand travel']",ServiceProvider,,['Wellington'],['Lower Hutt'],"The Wainuiomata Historical Society was established in 1977.  In March 1987 the Wellington Education Board gave the use of the ‘old school’, a 1908 heritage building, to the Society.  The Museum was opened on 30 September 1989 by Harry Martin, the first and only Mayor of Wainuiomata. The Museum is run by volunteers.  It aims to encourage the study of history and to foster public appreciation of local places and matters of historical interest. It does this by permanent preservation of a wide variety of objects and records and opening these to the public.  Welcomes helpers. Opens on Sunday from 2-4pm and by arrangement other times for school groups and others.  Entry fee is a gold coin to help with the upkeep.","

KB00040048,140.89587,Arohanui Strings - Sistema Hutt Valley,"Arohanui Strings - Sistema Hutt Valley is a registered charity that provides a music education and social development programme in the Hutt Valley and Wellington.  They take children, who might not otherwise have the opportunity to learn music, and help them to reach their potential through teamwork, harmony and ensemble playing. ",https://www.cab.org.nz/community-directory/KB00040048,False,True,"['special education', 'volunteering & community organisations', 'cultural activities']",ServiceProvider,,['Wellington'],['Lower Hutt'],"Arohanui Strings - Sistema Hutt Valley is a registered charity that provides a music education and social development programme in the Hutt Valley and Wellington.  They take children, who might not otherwise have the opportunity to learn music, and help them to reach their potential through teamwork, harmony and ensemble playing.  Their mission is ""to inspire children and youth to achieve their full potential, acquire values that favour their growth, and have a positive impact on both their lives and society"". Each child is given their own instrument and joins music classes held after school five days a week. Some 200 children from the primary, intermediate and secondary schools in the area take part.  Children learn violin, viola, cello, double bass, singing and music literacy helped by teachers, student and parent helpers, and other volunteers.   The group gives concerts and runs free holiday music courses. The programme is inspired by the Sistema model of teaching children music that was founded in Venezuela and is now widely used round the world.  ","

KB00038566,126.397736,Wellington Hindi School,"Classes are held in three locations: 27 Kings Cres Lower Hutt on Sundays 10:00am -12.00pm Newlands address to be confirmed - Sundays 10.00am - 12.00pm 39 Webb St. Mt Cook, Wellington on  Sundays 10am -12.00pm  ",https://www.cab.org.nz/community-directory/KB00038566,False,True,"['cultural activities', 'community finder']",ServiceProvider,,['Wellington'],[None],"The school exists to provide language and culture service to anyone who wants to learn Hindi and the associated cultures.  Most of classes are running online. The Wellington Hindi School’s award winning curriculum places learners and their families at the centre of the system. Their vision is to develop confident, connected, actively involved life-long learners who are integrated into the NZ community. They aspire to: •       Deliver a holistic approach to teaching and learning of Hindi and cultural values. •       Use innovative approaches, including technology, to improve teaching and learning. •       Align their Hindi programmes with the New Zealand school system. •       Integrate learners into the New Zealand social, cultural and economic environment. •       Expose  students to experiences outside the Hindi classroom to develop overall competence and confidence. •       Develop teacher and leadership capability through Professional Learning and Development opportunities. •       Collaborate with educators/Hindi schools/Hindi scholars in New Zealand and overseas to ensure that they are up to date with developments and trends. Classes are held in three locations: 27 Kings Cres Lower Hutt on Sundays 10:00am -12.00pm Newlands address to be confirmed - Sundays 10.00am - 12.00pm 39 Webb St. Mt Cook, Wellington on  Sundays 10am -12.00pm  ","

KB00038384,96.10572,Sisters of Compassion,"St Joseph's Home of Compassion rest home and hospital in Heretaunga, Lower Hutt is a care facility for elderly people which also caters for people with dementia Compassion Housing in Upper Hutt and Levin provides houses for elderly people at a discounted rate. The sisters also run the Chanel Home of Compassion in Fiji for the elderly and those with disabilities.  ",https://www.cab.org.nz/community-directory/KB00038384,False,True,"['for hire', 'care of older people', 'volunteering & community organisations', 'health and safety and volunteering', 'cultural activities', 'counselling and support groups', 'new zealand travel']",ServiceProvider,,['Wellington'],[None],"The Sisters of Compassion, also known as the Daughters of Our Lady of Compassion, was founded by Suzanne Aubert at Jerusalem, Hiruhārama on the Whanganui River in 1892. For more than a century the sisters have taught, nursed, and provided homes for children, the sick and the elderly in New Zealand and the South Pacific. They are committed to delivering ""compassionate care"" throughout the community by providing meals, food, and basic needs to those who have very little, caring for the elderly, and providing individual and family support. They seek to bring dignity to the lives of the aged, the powerless and the poor. They have the following facilities:- Our Lady's Home of Compassion, Island Bay, is our congregation's main office as well as being a conference and retreat centre.  A professional conference room seating 70 people lecture style and 30 people around tables, equipped with WiFi, audio/video and conference tables and chairs is available for half and full day meetings or workshops. Catering is available.         Accommodation sleeping 31 people, includes, single, double and twin share rooms with free breakfast, towels and WiFi.        It is also home to the Suzanne Aubert Heritage Centre which is free to visit. Coffee and simple homemade fare is available in the refreshment area. The centre is fully accessible. Onsite car parking available. The Compassion Centre in Wellington includes the city's soup kitchen. St Joseph's Home of Compassion rest home and hospital in Heretaunga, Lower Hutt is a care facility for elderly people which also caters for people with dementia Compassion Housing in Upper Hutt and Levin provides houses for elderly people at a discounted rate. The sisters also run the Chanel Home of Compassion in Fiji for the elderly and those with disabilities.  ","

KB00038403,92.4805,Sri Lanka Association of New Zealand (SLANZ) Inc,"Sri Lanka Association of New Zealand (SLANZ) inc objectives are to foster, facilitate and promote within New Zealand, the development of cultural values and traditions of Sri Lanka, especially among the younger Sri Lankans. SLANZ is not a political organization. It complements the work of other Sri Lankan associations in the country, providing cultural and social support to the wider Sri Lankan Community.",https://www.cab.org.nz/community-directory/KB00038403,False,True,"['cultural activities', 'community finder']",ServiceProvider,,['Wellington'],"['Lower Hutt', 'Upper Hutt', 'Wellington City']","Sri Lanka Association of New Zealand (SLANZ) inc objectives are to foster, facilitate and promote within New Zealand, the development of cultural values and traditions of Sri Lanka, especially among the younger Sri Lankans. SLANZ is not a political organization. It complements the work of other Sri Lankan associations in the country, providing cultural and social support to the wider Sri Lankan Community. In conjunction with its AGM in (August/September) they hold an annual cultural night. Other activities during the year include conducting traditional Sri Lankan dancing workshops, voice training workshops, classes in guitar, violin, stage drama and Tabla. SLANZ also participates in the local Waitangai Day celebrations at Orongomai Marae Intake process: Complete the online membership form here    ","

KB00008199,77.637726,Bodhinyanarama Buddhist Monastery,"Bodhinyanarama, the Garden of Enlightened Knowing, was founded in 1983. It is a monastic residence of the Theravada tradition of Buddhism in Stokes Valley, near Wellington. Visitors are welcome. The stupa or pagoda is five minutes from the car park.",https://www.cab.org.nz/community-directory/KB00008199,False,True,['cultural activities'],ServiceProvider,,['Nationwide'],[None],"Bodhinyanarama, the Garden of Enlightened Knowing, was founded in 1983. It is a monastic residence of the Theravada tradition of Buddhism in Stokes Valley, near Wellington. Visitors are welcome. The stupa or pagoda is five minutes from the car park. Its main purpose is as a residence for those taking part or training in the monastic lifestyle, but the large public area and meeting hall are also used for religious festivals, public meetings and retreats. The forested area with remote lodgings provides an environment for seclusion. The senior monks instruct in meditation, teach Buddhist principles, lead retreats and provide religious services for the Buddhist community, both at the monastery and at other venues The website gives details about contacting the Monastery and the various events visitors can attend. It is possible to stay at the Monastery.","

Bodhinyanarama, the Garden of Enlightened Knowing, was founded in 1983. It is a monastic residence of the Theravada tradition of Buddhism in Stokes Valley, near Wellington. Visitors are welcome. The stupa or pagoda is five minutes from the car park.

Its main purpose is as a residence for those taking part or training in the monastic lifestyle, but the large public area and meeting hall are also used for religious festivals, public meetings and retreats.

The forested area with remote lodgings provides an environment for seclusion. The senior monks instruct in meditation, teach Buddhist principles, lead retreats and provide religious services for the Buddhist community, both at the monastery and at other venues

The website gives details about contacting the Monastery and the various events visitors can attend. It is possible to stay at the Monastery.

KB00001907,3.9834783,How do I find a book group or writers' group in my area?,"Joining a book group can be a good way to ensure that you read books you might not otherwise read, and have the chance to discuss them with others. The Book Discussion Scheme website has a list of affiliated book groups. You can also try asking at your local public library.",https://www.cab.org.nz/article/KB00001907,False,True,['cultural activities'],QuestionAndAnswer,,[],[],"Joining a book group can be a good way to ensure that you read books you might not otherwise read, and have the chance to discuss them with others. The Book Discussion Scheme website has a list of affiliated book groups. You can also try asking at your local public library. If you want to start your own book group, you will find tips on the National Library website and the website of the publisher, Penguin. If you are interested in writing, whether professionally or just as a hobby, getting together with other writers is a good way to get advice, feedback and inspiration. You can find a list of writers groups on the New Zealand Society of Authors website. Their website also includes advice for starting your own writers' group. Your local CAB can also help you find a book club or writing group near you.","

KB00001909,3.9834783,What low cost leisure activities are available in my local area?,"Most communities provide the public access to a range of leisure areas, facilities and activities either for free or at a low cost - the range and type will of course vary from place to place. They may include museums, art galleries, libraries, botanic gardens, nature walks, public swimming pools, fairs and festivals – and more besides. ",https://www.cab.org.nz/article/KB00001909,False,True,['cultural activities'],QuestionAndAnswer,,[],[],"Most communities provide the public access to a range of leisure areas, facilities and activities either for free or at a low cost - the range and type will of course vary from place to place. They may include museums, art galleries, libraries, botanic gardens, nature walks, public swimming pools, fairs and festivals – and more besides.  Most councils provide information about the leisure areas, facilities and activities available in their local area. Some of these activities are available at a discount for people with low income (eg, if you have a Community Services Card). Contact your local CAB to find out what is available in your area.","

KB00001908,3.9834783,I am new to the area and want to link up with others with my cultural background. Is there a local group or organisation I can contact?,"If you are new to New Zealand you might consider joining the New Zealand Newcomers Network, which has groups all over New Zealand. They hold social events and activities to suit all ages, cultures and religions.",https://www.cab.org.nz/article/KB00001908,False,True,['cultural activities'],QuestionAndAnswer,,[],[],"If you are new to New Zealand you might consider joining the New Zealand Newcomers Network, which has groups all over New Zealand. They hold social events and activities to suit all ages, cultures and religions. Your local CAB will be able to provide you with information and contact details for any groups or organisations there may be in your local area for your ethnic group or culture. Or, you can search our online community directory for this information.  You can also search the Office of Ethnic Communities’ online directory for ethnic community groups around New Zealand.","

KB00041503,3.9834783,SIAOLA - Vahefonua Tonga Methodist Mission Charitable Trust ,"Vahefonua Tonga Methodist Mission Charitable Trust (SIAOLA) also known as Vahefonua Tonga o Aotearoa Methodist Mission Charitable Trust is a social service provider based in Central Auckland.  Their Fāmili Lelei are value based family centred services designed for Pacific people with a special focus on Tongan people and their families. All services are delivered in a culturally appropriate manner and address issues to build resilient safe and loving homes, where individuals and families can thrive.",https://www.cab.org.nz/community-directory/KB00041503,False,True,"['care and protection of children and young people', 'care of older people', 'volunteering & community organisations', 'cultural activities', 'budgeting']",ServiceProvider,,['Auckland'],[None],"Vahefonua Tonga Methodist Mission Charitable Trust (SIAOLA) also known as Vahefonua Tonga o Aotearoa Methodist Mission Charitable Trust is a social service provider based in Central Auckland.  Their Fāmili Lelei are value based family centred services designed for Pacific people with a special focus on Tongan people and their families. All services are delivered in a culturally appropriate manner and address issues to build resilient safe and loving homes, where individuals and families can thrive. Family Services - address family violence prevention, support for vulnerable families, youth support. Educational Services - Early childhood centres, mentoring programmes for years 1-13, trade and apprenticeship pastoral care. KB00018831,3.9834783,Wellington City Libraries,Eleven suburban libraries operate in Wellington.,https://www.cab.org.nz/community-directory/KB00018831,False,True,"['early childhood education', 'local government', 'cultural activities', 'disability assistance']",ServiceProvider,,['Wellington'],['Wellington City'],"Eleven suburban libraries operate in Wellington. The main library in Wellington City has been closed because of earthquake risk and pop-up library services are operating for inner city residents and workers. Currently they are:- Arapaki Manners Library He Matapihi Molesworth Library Te Awe Library  Internet (free for 60 minutes), free Wifi, printing and faxing facilities are available at all libraries. Services and activities are similar throughout. Some popular library services are:- Kids activities:- Baby Rock & Rhyme, preschool story times, holiday activities and book clubs  Migrant information: The library has material to help people learn English, and a growing collection of books, newspapers and DVDs in other languages. People can request an interpreter when visiting the Library. Some libraries have social English Groups. Prosearch:- Research services for businesses and individuals. This services is useful for people wanting to start a new business. Their Business Information Specialist offer business research which access demographic and promotion information for business ideas. They also offer one hour free, one on one training to people wanting to access this information for themselves. Library services for people with disability:- These include housebound services for permanently disabled, talking books, library express, cassettes, CDs, DVDs and videos, large print, audio visual material, talking books. Books are delivered to the closest library to the client, then delivered by volunteers. Eligibility: Wellington Residents","

KB00042964,3.9834783,Mid Canterbury Country Music Club,"People of all ages are welcome to come along for an afternoon of country music with a live band. You can sing, with members having first priority, or just enjoy an afternoon of entertainment. No experience is required and there are members who are happy to help guide you. The club provides a band, sound, microphones, etc. but you are more than welcome to bring along your own instrument.",https://www.cab.org.nz/community-directory/KB00042964,False,True,"['volunteering & community organisations', 'health and safety and volunteering', 'cultural activities']",ServiceProvider,,['Canterbury'],['Ashburton'],"People of all ages are welcome to come along for an afternoon of country music with a live band. You can sing, with members having first priority, or just enjoy an afternoon of entertainment. No experience is required and there are members who are happy to help guide you. The club provides a band, sound, microphones, etc. but you are more than welcome to bring along your own instrument. You could even learn a new skill like operating the sound desk or how to set up/pack down the musical equipment. As well as regular club days they also try to organise a variety of events throughout the year for members to enjoy. In previous years this has included subsidised bus trips and meals, shared lunches, picnics, and performances at local events such as Plains Railway Museum Christmas Celebration. Membership is not required to attend club days, however new members are welcome. Feel free to come along to the next club day (Usually advertised in the Ashburton Courier). Members receive regular newsletters, special events, and an invitation to the AGM & Christmas celebration every December. Fees Membership is $20 per person, or $35 per family (within the same household). Raffles are available for purchase on the day ($2 a ticket). Food and beverage available for purchase from the bar and/or restaurant.","

An outdoor crater observatory in the Omaka Valley. Venue has been created to help generations to come to appreciate the dark sky on our door step.

Free access will be offered to school groups, whist also running a tourism stargazing business. A standard tours of one hour is limited to a maximum of 18 people. Tickets can be purchased online or through the Picton and Blenheim i sites.

There is no private transport permitted to the site. Their bus picks patrons from the Blenheim Railway Station (opposite the i-site) with a second pick up point at the Runway Cafe on Middle Renwick Road.

The Trust also operates an Astronomy club which holds meetings on the first Monday of every month in Marlborough. These meetings will include the opportunity to meet others, listen to talks and use a range of telescopes.

KB00042832,3.9834783,Te Ngākau Kahukura,"Te Ngākau Kahukura is a national initiative developed in partnership with rainbow communities to make communities, environments and systems more safe and inclusive. They aim to create system change by lobbying funders, decision makers, training providers and sector bodies that provide health and social services.",https://www.cab.org.nz/community-directory/KB00042832,False,True,"['help for small business', 'volunteering & community organisations', 'cultural activities', 'services', 'community finder']",ServiceProvider,,['Nationwide'],[None],"Te Ngākau Kahukura is a national initiative developed in partnership with rainbow communities to make communities, environments and systems more safe and inclusive. They aim to create system change by lobbying funders, decision makers, training providers and sector bodies that provide health and social services. They work collaboratively with professionals, organisations and wider systems that support people across Aotearoa, including health, housing, social, education and justice to support and be more inclusive of rainbow people.  They help rainbow community organisations to build their capacity and connections but do not provide services directly to individuals themselves. Contact via website form www.tengakaukahukura.nz/need-more Te Ngākau Kahukura within the organisational structure of Ara Taiohi.  ","

KB00042787,3.9834783,Paeroa - Historical Maritime Park Inc ,"A local museum, run by volunteers, based in Paeroa within a garden/park setting beside the river. The museum is  home to a collection of Maritime history relating to the role that Paeroa played as a port for unloading mining machinery and equipment in the late 19th century.  ",https://www.cab.org.nz/community-directory/KB00042787,False,True,"['for hire', 'volunteering & community organisations', 'cultural activities', 'new zealand travel']",ServiceProvider,,['Waikato'],['Hauraki'],"A local museum, run by volunteers, based in Paeroa within a garden/park setting beside the river. The museum is  home to a collection of Maritime history relating to the role that Paeroa played as a port for unloading mining machinery and equipment in the late 19th century.   There is a cycle link to/from Hauraki Rail Trail. Self contained camper vans can stay over night on the park grounds for $20/night (plus $5 if power required) River cruises - 3 different vessels including a paddle boat (the Tamati) are available for cruising the Ohinemuri and Waihou Rivers. The venue is available for hire and with the river view, park grounds and gardens would be suitable for weddings and private functions wanting to make the most of the indoor and outdoor setting. Each year in December a Christmas Light show is held in the park.  This is a ticketed event which raises funds for the upkeep of the park. Entry fees to the museum and grounds apply - Family (2 adults, 2 children) - $20","

KB00042746,3.9834783,Buller District Library ,"The Library provides public library services at two main locations in Buller, the district library in Westport (Sue Thomson Casey Memorial Library) and a branch library in Reefton (Inangahua County Library).  Membership provides access to the collections at both libraries as well as the digital and audio collections.  Library and information services to the community include:",https://www.cab.org.nz/community-directory/KB00042746,False,True,"['local government', 'cultural activities']",ServiceProvider,,['West Coast'],['Buller'],"The Library provides public library services at two main locations in Buller, the district library in Westport (Sue Thomson Casey Memorial Library) and a branch library in Reefton (Inangahua County Library).  Membership provides access to the collections at both libraries as well as the digital and audio collections.  Library and information services to the community include: Free internet and computing (6 computers at Westport and 3 at Reefton) Printing (charges apply) Assistance with RealMe and MyAccount in collaboration with Work and income. Stepping UP computer classes – free computer & internet training Better Digital Futures for Seniors classes for people aged 65+ to learn new skills and build confidence with computers and the internet. Assistance to apply for Skinny Jump – prepay home broadband with no contract, no credit checks and no set-up charges. Membership of the libraries is free for all ratepayers and permanent residents of Buller District.","

KB00042643,3.9834783,Kaikōura Museum ,"The Kaikōura Museum is a state of the art Museum that showcases Kaikōura’s diverse natural, social and cultural journey. The long term display highlights the areas connection to the sea. They also have some uniquely Kaikōura artefacts on display. The museum also holds the districts archives, these can be accessed for research.",https://www.cab.org.nz/community-directory/KB00042643,False,True,"['special education', 'cultural activities']",ServiceProvider,,['Marlborough'],['Kaikoura'],"The Kaikōura Museum is a state of the art Museum that showcases Kaikōura’s diverse natural, social and cultural journey. The long term display highlights the areas connection to the sea. They also have some uniquely Kaikōura artefacts on display. The museum also holds the districts archives, these can be accessed for research. They have two venues available for hire. small auditorium for groups of up to 50 people. Includes AV equipment. A room suitable for meetings of up to 8 people. Accessibility:  Wheelchair accessible , two accessible parks directly outside the building, a loan wheelchair available. Fees: Adults: $12.00 Gold Card, Students, Community Service Card: $10.00 Children: $6.00 Family: $30.00 (2 adults and up to 4 school aged children) Kaikōura residents only pay half price, with proof, for entrance.   ","

KB00042556,3.9834783,No.24 (Ashburton) Squadron Air Training Corps,"Cadet Units offer a wide variety of training and experiences that are unique to the Cadet Force, and teach life and work skills that open up new possibilities, opportunities and career options. Cadets learn to be part of a team, develop leadership and survival skills, make new friends, experience challenges and learn to take responsibility.",https://www.cab.org.nz/community-directory/KB00042556,False,True,"['volunteering & community organisations', 'sport', 'cultural activities']",ServiceProvider,,['Canterbury'],['Ashburton'],"Cadet Units offer a wide variety of training and experiences that are unique to the Cadet Force, and teach life and work skills that open up new possibilities, opportunities and career options. Cadets learn to be part of a team, develop leadership and survival skills, make new friends, experience challenges and learn to take responsibility. Air Cadet Units hold activities throughout the year, including outdoor and adventure training such as: Parade Nights - Every unit holds Parade Nights weekly, approximately 3–4 hours per night during the school terms. Powered Flying and Gliding- Air Cadet Units typically organise practical Flying or Gliding Training for the cadets in partnership with local Aero Clubs. Aviation Syllabus - Cadets will learn aviation history, how engines work, aircraft technology, air navigation, air field layout, weather maps, aviation radio and more. Bushcraft - Air Cadet Units give their cadets the opportunity to become skilled and comfortable in the bush environment. Theory lessons and scenarios are supported with camps run throughout the year, each providing new and exciting activities and skills. Firearms Safety and Marksmanship Training - Units conduct regular firearms safety and shooting skills training. Duke of Edinburgh - All training provided by the NZCF can be cross-credited to those who are working towards their Duke of Edinburgh’s Hillary Award. The Air Training Corps (ATC), commonly known as Air Cadets, is the arm of the New Zealand Cadet Forces (NZCF) aligned with the Royal New Zealand Air Force (RNZAF) Eligibility :13–15-year-olds are welcome to apply. ","

Cadet Units offer a wide variety of training and experiences that are unique to the Cadet Force, and teach life and work skills that open up new possibilities, opportunities and career options. Cadets learn to be part of a team, develop leadership and survival skills, make new friends, experience challenges and learn to take responsibility.

Air Cadet Units hold activities throughout the year, including outdoor and adventure training such as:

  • Parade Nights - Every unit holds Parade Nights weekly, approximately 3–4 hours per night during the school terms.
• Powered Flying and Gliding- Air Cadet Units typically organise practical Flying or Gliding Training for the cadets in partnership with local Aero Clubs.
• Aviation Syllabus - Cadets will learn aviation history, how engines work, aircraft technology, air navigation, air field layout, weather maps, aviation radio and more.

• Bushcraft - Air Cadet Units give their cadets the opportunity to become skilled and comfortable in the bush environment. Theory lessons and scenarios are supported with camps run throughout the year, each providing new and exciting activities and skills.
• Firearms Safety and Marksmanship Training - Units conduct regular firearms safety and shooting skills training.
• Duke of Edinburgh - All training provided by the NZCF can be cross-credited to those who are working towards their Duke of Edinburgh’s Hillary Award.

The Air Training Corps (ATC), commonly known as Air Cadets, is the arm of the New Zealand Cadet Forces (NZCF) aligned with the Royal New Zealand Air Force (RNZAF)

Eligibility :13–15-year-olds are welcome to apply.
